props.synopsis: Brisbane alone is home to as many people as Tasmania, the ACT and NT combined — so it's no surprise one of the biggest issues the south-east Queensland is facing is population growth and development.

title.children: WATCH: South-east Queensland is being inundated with people from interstate. So how can it keep up?

image.altText: a woman standing in front of a christmas tree in a white dress

props.synopsis: The brakes of a bus that crashed in Brisbane's CBD were tested last month, and its driver had a "strong performance record" over a decades-long career, according to the city's council.

title.children: Brisbane bus crash victim Tia Cameron's family say 18-year-old 'tragically stolen from us'

image.altText: Composite image of Premier Steven Miles and Opposition Leader David Crisafulli

props.synopsis: Despite the best efforts of newly minted Premier Steven Miles to make a fresh start, incumbency could be a stumbling block for the government in two upcoming by-elections.

title.children: 'Send a strong message': Why a Labor seat could be in play in Queensland's upcoming by-election

image.altText: an aerial shot of a sinkhole under a commercial building in Rockdale

props.synopsis: A landslide occurs on the airport side of West Botany Street in Rockdale, about 150 metres away from where a similar incident happened on March 1.

title.children: Sinkhole opens in Sydney's south just days after similar incident

image.altText: A large apartment building during the day time.

props.synopsis: A penthouse apartment formerly owned by late Sydney conwoman Melissa Caddick has been sold, with the proceeds to be used to pay back some of the money stolen from dozens of investors.

title.children: Fraudster Melissa Caddick's luxury Sydney penthouse sold

image.altText: Three children sit with their hands cable tied. Their faces are blurred.

props.synopsis: The video was live streamed across social media and showed three primary school aged, tear-streaked children tied together at their wrists with cable ties, waiting for police to show up.

title.children: How did we get here? The Broome incident that was 'confronting' and 'disturbing'

image.altText: A person wearing a Winnie the Pooh mask looking down at the camera in a darkly-lit space.

props.synopsis: A horror film based on the beloved children's literary character Winnie the Pooh claims five categories at the annual awards.

title.children: The worst films and performances of the year, according to the Razzie awards

image.altText: Police tape

props.synopsis: Police reopened the investigation into the three-month-old's death after receiving new information this earlier year. An investigation at the time was inconclusive.

title.children: Woman charged with murdering baby girl south-east of Brisbane 13 years ago after tip-off

image.altText: Three women stand acting, while other people sit on couches behind.

props.synopsis: Silk Rags encourages audiences to laugh, cry and learn as it tackles the difficult subject matter of cancer, and what to say or not to say when a loved one is diagnosed.

title.children: If a friend received a cancer diagnosis, what would you say? This musical tackles the difficult subject

image.altText: Police car on dirt road and hint of bin and cloth to side of road

props.synopsis: Victoria Police are investigating a suspected murder after a woman's body was found in a bin on a remote regional road.

title.children: Murder investigation underway after woman's body found in bin in regional Victoria

image.altText: A smiling woman with two children, their faces pixelated

props.synopsis: Ballarat locals are being encouraged to reach out for help as they struggle to process the disappearance of Samantha Murphy and arrest of a local man.

title.children: Grief over Samantha Murphy is complicated by arrest of local man, Ballarat mayor says

image.altText: Jason Palmer

props.synopsis: Self-described long-shot candidate Jason Palmer won over American Samoa with virtual town halls and campaigners on the ground. Now he wants to follow up his victory in another US territory in the Pacific.

title.children: American Samoa backs candidate with chances likened to 'ant trying to build a spaceship'

image.altText: ECQ logo on an envelope for a postal vote.

props.synopsis: With so many councillor and mayor positions uncontested, is it a sign of voter disengagement or are people happy with how things are?

title.children: It's a well-paid job so why are fewer people nominating for local councils?

image.altText: Two police officers walking up a driveway

props.synopsis: Police who shot and killed a young woman to stop her from stabbing her mother acted appropriately, Victoria Police say.

title.children: Victoria Police defend officers involved in fatal shooting of woman found stabbing her mother

image.altText: A man stands in a white shirt.

props.synopsis: Court documents reveal a new star witness has come forward alleging one of the men accused of bikie heavyweight Shane Bowden's murder claimed while behind bars he was paid for his alleged role in the killing.

title.children: Details emerge of alleged jailhouse confession over the killing of bikie Shane Bowden

image.altText: A CQ Rescue staff member sits at the side of a helicopter as it flies over a body of water.

props.synopsis: A rescue helicopter joins police and other emergency services in the search for a man missing in a boating mishap at a popular north Queensland dam.

title.children: Man missing in dam near Mackay after falling out of boat with daughter, 9

image.altText: A man with close cropped hair, aviators on forehead, blue hoodie stands looking at the camera, slight smile on face, stubble.

props.synopsis: Dougie Hampson died less than 24-hours after he was misdiagnosed with a cannabis-related syndrome and discharged from Dubbo hospital in August 2021. A coroner has spent two weeks hearing about what led to his death.

title.children: Was racism and bias behind the misdiagnosis of Indigenous man who died less than 24 hours after leaving hospital?

image.altText: man walking through fields of crop

props.synopsis: Water is critical to running a successful farm and these 14 Tasmanian farmers have found a way to make sure they won't struggle obtaining it again.

title.children: Farmers' brainwave transforms once-dry region to dairy and grape country

image.altText: Three hands sifting through tiny stones.

props.synopsis: Many "mum and dad" prospectors say fossicking is a chance to spend time with family and friends. But big changes are looming that could put the brakes on small-scale miners.

title.children: No-one really expects to strike it rich, but weekend miners say their right to try is under threat

image.altText: A man stands with a sling on his right shoulder

props.synopsis: Canterbury fear Josh Addo-Carr has "broken something" in his shoulder, while St George Illawarra dominate the Titans in their first match under new coach Shane Flaganan.

title.children: Bulldogs fear the worst for Addo-Carr after loss to Eels, Dragons dominate Titans

image.altText: A group of Giants AFL players grin as they run back to the middle after a goal.

props.synopsis: The AFL's Opening Round comes to an end with GWS taking care of Collingwood getting a measure of revenge for last year's prelim final loss. Earlier, the Suns got off to a winning start under Damien Hardwick, beating Richmond.

title.children: 'We learned some really good lessons': Pies look to bounce back after Giants dominate, as Hardwick gets one up on the Tigers

image.altText: A drone shot that shows a bridge over the Murray River leading into the town of Robinvale.

props.synopsis: A man has died at a water skiing race during the Euston Robinvale 80 on the Victoria and New South Wales border.

title.children: Man dies in water skiing incident during race on Murray River

image.altText: Crowd at a music festival - good generic

props.synopsis: Melbourne's iconic Moomba Parade has been cancelled to ensure safety in extreme heat this weekend.

title.children: Moomba Parade cancelled and thousands of music fans advised to leave festivals amid heatwave

image.altText: Burst of red light in night sky with thunderstorm in the background

props.synopsis: Nature photographer JJ Rao was out shooting a wet-season thunderstorm just outside of Derby when he was lucky enough to snap several red sprites, one of the world's rarest natural phenomena.

title.children: Spectacular 'nature's neon lights' caught on camera over WA outback

image.altText: Lambo Kanagaratnam a man in a suit sitting in front of a microphone.

props.synopsis: Lambo Kanagaratnam is the latest top-level executive to resign in the wake of a mass outage which left 10 million customers and 400,000 businesses without phone or internet service.

title.children: Optus networks director resigns four months after mass outage

image.altText: Max Verstappen in a dark blue Red Bull, during a night race in Saudi Arabia, going through a corner.

props.synopsis: Verstappen is not threatened around the streets of Jeddah, finishing ahead of teammate Sergio Perez and Ferrari's Charles Leclerc who rounded out the podium.

title.children: Verstappen cruises to another win as Piastri claims fourth in Jeddah

image.altText: Glenn Phillips is surrounded by teammates and all smile

props.synopsis: Marnus Labuschagne answers some critics and Kane Williamson misses a golden opportunity, but Glenn Phillips steals the show with a catch to remember. Here are five quick hits from day two in Christchurch.

title.children: Five quick hits — A catch for the ages, Labuschagne finds form and Cummins breaks Williamson's heart

image.altText: Jeffrey, right, looks to the left concerned, Emma looks to the right pensively, with Da'Vine on the right looking serious.

props.synopsis: What is Australia if not the land of delayed film releases? We asked two experts to dish on the reasons it can sometimes take days, weeks or months until international films make it to our cinemas.

title.children: Why do we still have to wait so long for films when they're already out in the US?

image.altText: A lonely chef chops vegetables in a commercial kitchen

props.synopsis: Stress, poor pay and job insecurity are driving chefs away from the hospitality industry — and tourism will bear the brunt of this looming skill shortage.

title.children: Overworked, underpaid and exhausted: Why chefs are leaving the hospitality industry

image.altText: A man taking a selfie in front of floodwater.

props.synopsis: Parry Creek Farm resort and caravan park owner Mark Dyson keeps an eye out for two resident crocodiles, as he's forced to canoe across his flooded property after big rain in WA's Kimberley.

title.children: Manager uses dinghy and canoe to paddle in crocodile waters to check on tourist park

image.altText: Composite image of Sam Docherty (left) and Keidean Coleman.

props.synopsis: Both the Blues and Lions are counting the cost of Friday night's thrilling match at the Gabba, with Sam Docherty and Keidean Coleman both suffering ACL injuries.

title.children: Carlton, Brisbane Lions hit with season-ending injuries in Opening Round

image.altText: A before and after shot showing a close-up of Jayden Vilardi before and after he had eight veneers fitted to his top teeth.

props.synopsis: Jayden Vilardi says he didn’t rush into getting teeth veneers and was told of the risks, however concerns are mounting about persuasive advertising enticing others to get the procedure.

title.children: Jayden spent $21,000 on dental veneers to have the perfect smile. But it's an industry under scrutiny

image.altText: A close up of Kate Middleton smiling while wearing dangly earings.

props.synopsis: For centuries, the British monarchy has shrouded itself in mystery while allowing the occasional glimpse over palace walls. But when the star royal wanted to convalesce in private, some of her future subjects revolted.

title.children: The House of Windsor has long contended with wild conspiracy theories, but the frenzy around Kate's health is beyond public interest

image.altText: A black and white photo of a metallic disk flying through the sky

props.synopsis: A Pentagon report on unidentified flying objects says US government investigations since the end of World War II have found no evidence of extraterrestrial technology.

title.children: Pentagon says most UFOs are misidentified ordinary objects

image.altText: Raye sitting down wearing long maroon high heeled boots, a grey guitar, drum kit and speakers behind her

props.synopsis: British singer-songwriter Raye made history when she won six Brit Awards this week. It's been a long road to the top for the pop star, who was on the verge of giving up her dream before her breakthrough and awards dominance.

title.children: Raye's recognition at the Brit Awards was borne out of blood, sweat and years
